text:
hot news
bermaksud membela diri terkait gerakan me too, rani mukerji malah diserang netizen di twitter ğŸ˜¯

rani mukherjee, tabu, deepika padukone, anushka sharma, taapsee pannu dan alia bhatt adalah aktris terbaik tahun 2018 dengan katakter film yang mereka tampilkan. mereka dikumpulkan jadi satu di meja bundar aktris terbaik 2018 dan ditanya untuk berdiskusi masalah apapun yang terjadi di industri bollywood selama tahun 2018.

disaat meluncur sebuah pertanyaan dari panitia perihal gerakan #metoo , rani mukerji yang tidak setuju dengan pendapat yang dilontarkan deepika padukone dan anushka sharma membuat netizen membanting serangan kepada rani di twitter karena komentar 'membela diri'. #metoo adalah sebuah gerakan dimana terkait dengan isu pelecehan seksual yang dilakukan oleh tokoh-tokoh industri. semua korban dan pelaku bersaing mengujar kejujuran atas kebungkaman yang selama ini mereka sembunyikan. beberapa korban dan pelaku pelecehan seksual satu demi satu terungkap dengan adanya gerakan ini.

rani mukerji adalah sosok aktris yang memiliki kepribadian yang masih sangat dicintai berkat pesona yang dibawanya dari tahun 90an dan masih berhasil memenangkan hati di layar sinema sampai saat ini, tetapi aktris 40 tahun ini pasti memiliki sudut pandang berbeda pada gerakan #metoo yang berlangsung sepanjang tahun 2018 ini, yang tidak dihargai oleh kebanyakan orang.

anushka, deepika, rani, alia, tabu dan taapsee dipanggil pada pertemuan konferensi meja bundar, dimana ia mendapatkan topik yang menjadi salah satu sorotan terbesar tahun 2018, dan berkaitan dengan selebriti wanita. anushka, deepika dan alia telah mendukung gerakan itu sebelumnya dan mereka menyatakan bahwa gerakan #metoo adalah langkah yang baik, karena sekarang orang akan berpikir dua kali sebelum bertindak di sekitar wanita.

namun, rani yang datang ke konferensi atas predikat salah satu aktris terbaik tahun 2018 dalam perannya di film hichki sebagai guru yang berdiri tegak untuk murid-muridnya yang gaduh, membuat poin yang tampak sangat aneh bagi kebanyakan ora..(selengkapnya baca difacebook) ğŸ˜‰

text:
the year of women. 
2018 marked another historic uprising of female voices, another high-point of the women's revolution that is taking place across the world. 2018 was the year of women. 
2018 was remarkable year for our movement as we celebrated the 10th anniversary of #femen. the first decade of our history ends with pride for numerous fights against male domination, with sisterhood among the activists in 4 corners of the planet and with dreams and aspirations for the future. from ukraine to france and to the rest of the world. from kiev students, to women of different age and backgrounds in france, germany, spain, sweden, netherlands, belgium, mexico, brazil, turkey, canada, usa, venezuela and czech republic. that's the journey femen made so far and we are ready to expand further. 
in 2018, femen continued to give a sextremist lesson to the patriarchs in power like turkish president recep #erdogan and the us president donald #trump. driving across the champs-elysees in paris, trump's motorcade was stoped twice by our angry political bodies. that's our female revenge. that's how we grab back patriarchy by the balls! 
in 2018 femen also contributed to the worldwide female uprising #metoo. our activists chased the celebrity perpetrators and made sure they learn that female bodies aren't always sexual objects at their disposal. we made them hear angry loud female voices. following our actions against woody allen and roman polanski, in 2018 we've faced again silvio berlusconi and finally caught bill cosby as he was about to be sentenced for numerous crimes. 
in 2018 we've denounced homophobia of conservative groups who deny the rights of gay couples for medically assisted procreation in france as well as the hate crimes against lgbt+ community in putin's russia, in tunisia and egypt. we've defended our abortion rights with protests in germany and spain and raised up against xenophobia and sexism of the far right groups across europe. 
in 2018 we stood with heroes of freedom of speech and consciences like asia bibi in pakistan and oleg sentsov in russia. femen also supported the imprisoned in france artist pyotr pavlensky. 
the world was shakenâ¬‡

text:
new years is here! itâ€™s a time for new beginnings... so i have a confession to make to each of you. 
initially, i told you that i started my blog to update friends & fam on my whereaboots over my 6-month backpacking trip. but, that wasnâ€™t the truth.

the true reason i created my blog was.... to take off my mask! i was hiding who i am because i felt ashamed of the things i do in my life. not because they are immoral (far from it!), but because theyâ€™re totally unconventional; theyâ€™re beyond the conventions imposed on me by my childhood community; theyâ€™re outside the cultural norms of the corporate world i work in. 
i had fears of what people would think of me if they knew... theyâ€™d think iâ€™m crazy; theyâ€™d assume iâ€™m some sort of gypsy! i was suffering from constantly hiding in fear and shame... yet, i was the only one bestowing this shame onto myself, so only i have the power to remove my veil of shame!
i mean, shit, why should i feel ashamed of the things iâ€™ve done when i find them to be so absolutely incredible?!
from enjoying the life of bucket showers & no toilet paper in remote villages, to reciting a gratitude prayer before each meal. 
from my passion for budget vagabonding travel, to my passion for self-development through meditation, free-form dance, & quitting alcohol. ...i love the unconventional me that i am, the full spectrum â¤ï¸ğŸ¤² #booty

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the effos made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to cou documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the cou documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
in a superdeeduper eww of a session with b-town's biggest talents all on one table, ms. mukherjee, erstwhile on the list of artists i felt had integrity on screen and off, managed to do one of the best displays of foot-in-mouth i have seen. 
the topic up for discussion was  #metoo and the instance of harassment.
'i think you have to have the courage to be able to protect yourself' she says, to which deepika says not everyone is built with that dna and may feel cornered. 
rani of cringe: 'that's why we need to talk to these women and tell them they need to change.'
so. ms. mukherjee would rather the onus be shifted to the victims. classic internalised misogyny at its absolute finest. 
someone offers a contradicting opinion. actually, everyone on the table does. but nope. 
in life we need to take responsibility of our own selves, she opines. 
keeps on insisting that krav maga and martial arts classes be made compulsory in schools, in response to everyone and their mom telling her that the root issue needs to be countered. 
her victim-blaming rhetoric comes from an obnoxiously privileged place. physical strength, class protection, not having to be in public on your own, not having to take public transportation every single day. 
all of this is privilege. the thing that's causing her to verbal vomit this utter load of crap.
this is the least endearing a human can be to me. 
rani, sweetie, you're a cringefest and a trainwreck rolled into one. 
_______________________________

the students of howard university film and television program call for the establishment of a department of cinematic arts and television, effective fall 2019. howard has the most comprehensive film program, and offers the only mfa in film, of any hbcu in the united states. howard university has the only minority owned pbs affiliate in the nation. for decades since the founding of the film program in 1971, we have been fulfilling a national and global need for women storytellers and storytellers of color. still, there is no hbcu in the united states with a department dedicated to the study of cinematic arts and television - we can change this.

we are calling for the first department of cinematic arts and television, at any hbcu in the nation, to include the following components:

a) independently administered budget. 
b) independently managed equipment center and facilities. 
c) shared governance by the students and faculty over said budget, equipment center, curriculum development and implementation of the undergraduate and graduate bfa and mfa programs, as well as program and instructor evaluation. 
d) and a commitment to attract more of the most qualified professors in the industry, and to continue to produce graduates of the finest caliber.

support us by signing the petition, share the campaign with everyone you know, and let howard university president wayne a. i. frederick know that the time is now for a howard university department of cinematic arts and television.

why is this important?

since 1971, the howard university film program has produced and/or supported the most highly trained and widely acclaimed storytellers, including: bradford young, hans charles, ernest dickerson, arthur jafa, jenn nkiru, malik sayeed, alan ferguson, sehkar kammula, faraday okoro, lodi matsetela, lekgetho makola, nijla mumin, maori karmael holmes, floyd rance, yao ramesar, and shirikiana aina.

with the likes of stanley nelson, michelle parkerson, julie dash, and haile gerima having served as faculty in the program.

in the new era of #oscarssowhite, #timesup, and #metoo the film and television industry is clearing space to...

there are days when i struggle more than others. days when things that i've tried to bury so deep within myself surface. days that i feel like i just can't do the hard things. those are the times i reach for sara. it may help individuals release and begin recovery from tramatic memory of sexual or ritual torment or other forms of  physical or emotional abuse. for me it's a necessary tool. it help me with emotional release, emotional healing and relaxation. 
i don't typically share about this part of my past because there is alot of shame for victims, alot of judgement but also so many of us that have been there. if my saying #metoo helps just one person then my putting these words out there is worth it. if you are struggling with any of these things and need a shoulder i will gladly be here for you. i don't care if i haven't talked to you in forever or if i've never met you, i am here. 
be well friends

text:
and so the story goes they wore the clothes
they said the things to make it seem improbable
whale of a lie like they hope it was
and the good men tomorrow had their feet in the wallow
and their heads of brawn were nicer shorn
and how they bought their positions with saccharin and trust
and the world was asleep to our latent fuss
sighings swirl through the streets like the crust of the sun, the bewlay brothers
in our wings that bark
flashing teeth of brass
standing tall in the dark
oh, and we were gone
hanging out with your dwarf men
we were so turned on
by your lack of conclusions

i was stone and he was wax so he could scream and still relax
unbelievable
and we frightened the small children away
and our talk was old and dust would flow
through our veins and though it was midnight back at the kitchen door
like the grim face on the cathedral floor
the solid book we wrote cannot be found today
and it was stalking time for the moon boys, the bewlay brothers
with our backs on the arch
and if the devil may be here
but he can't sing about that
oh, and we were gone
real cool traders
we were so turned on
you thought we were fakers

and now the dress is hung, the ticket pawned
the factor max that proved the fact is melted down
woven on the edging of my pillow
and my brother lays upon the rocks
he could be dead, he could be not, he could be you
he's chameleon, comedian, corinthian and caricature
shooting up pie in the sky
bewlay brothers
in the feeble, in the bad
bewlay brothers ... .
.
.
david bowie

text:
and so the story goes they wore the clothes
they said the things to make it seem improbable
whale of a lie like they hope it was
and the good men tomorrow had their feet in the wallow
and their heads of brawn were nicer shorn
and how they bought their positions with saccharin and trust
and the world was asleep to our latent fuss
sighings swirl through the streets like the crust of the sun, the bewlay brothers
in our wings that bark
flashing teeth of brass
standing tall in the dark
oh, and we were gone
hanging out with your dwarf men
we were so turned on
by your lack of conclusions

i was stone and he was wax so he could scream and still relax
unbelievable
and we frightened the small children away
and our talk was old and dust would flow
through our veins and though it was midnight back at the kitchen door
like the grim face on the cathedral floor
the solid book we wrote cannot be found today
and it was stalking time for the moon boys, the bewlay brothers
with our backs on the arch
and if the devil may be here
but he can't sing about that
oh, and we were gone
real cool traders
we were so turned on
you thought we were fakers

and now the dress is hung, the ticket pawned
the factor max that proved the fact is melted down
woven on the edging of my pillow
and my brother lays upon the rocks
he could be dead, he could be not, he could be you
he's chameleon, comedian, corinthian and caricature
shooting up pie in the sky
bewlay brothers
in the feeble, in the bad
bewlay brothers ... .
.
.
david bowie

text: a thought twists upon a single line stretching toward infinity...as that is what the mind does when it supposes what existed when the heartbeat was brand new. those seconds of untouched wonder, when the world first appeared with an original breath, and then wended toward the next. how many of these baby breaths uncurled languidly before they were shocked by a wound is an open question and one that lies restless waiting on an answer. supposing through minute-years is a war with patience, masochism, or hope, without option of veering from the infinite line we twist upon.

ironic?? no...there's always a deeper meaning that can't be seen below the surface. only with spiritual eyes we get to understand the reason of certain circumstances. almost a year ago i a decision of getting this tattoo, everyone including the owner of the parlor asked me why "arabic" what does it mean?...i never really told anyone the true personal meaning behind it and it's in my right shoulder. the mark on my body is in honor of all women who have been and continue to be abused in the middle east, even as i write this. in honor to those women without a voice, forced to be in a arranged marriage. i carry them not only in my heart but with me their pain on my shoulder.

is when we stop in a place of silence that we get to understand what a soul is screaming. the pain, imprisonment of a broken heart...like a child waiting for love and to be nurtured. is a soul hoping for someone to break the chains, wanting so bad to be free. the child is still in there hiding deep under her beautiful big eyes, she doesn't understand that she's not alone, there's a hand being extended to pull her out. the child is screaming to break free. the universe is always conspiring to make it happen.â¤

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the companyâ€™s role on trumpâ€™s election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with â€œjudith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured selfâ€. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanelâ€™s little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum â€“ which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a â€œpre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time periodâ€. he conceded that while cambridge analytica â€œexploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put outâ€, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: â€œwe need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversityâ€ in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust â€“ and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
just saw this for some reason, it really hurt me... i never feel safe walking alone in pure daylight, never mind night time, just a few weeks ago i was leaving college and walking to the car when a car with two men stopped me to tell me how good i looked (and then they said some other horrific things) and i was terrified. i truly thought iâ€™m that moment that i might be kidnapped and die. it makes me so sad and so angry. and now that i think of it, iâ€™m not so sure i ever feel safe. iâ€™m nervous when a man sits next to me and looks in my direction. iâ€™m always extra cautious about whoâ€™s following me, and when ever i leave the house my mom reminds me to â€œbe aware of my surroundings â€œ. iâ€™m always on edge. even in the gym, or just anywhere in public, where men are around me. how does everyone else feel about this? do you ever feel safe? comment below

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
no hands are tearing your soul apart anymore.
â¤
no teeth are scrapping your mind to pieces.
â¤
stop destroying yourself.
please.
â¤
no monster is at home...no more, no more.
â¤
those parts of you, that believed the bleeding tales that danced around the notes of love hurts, and the lies that shouted how abandonment and survival are life...
â¤
those hands touched you were innocence should have stayedâ€¦
instead you traded cotton candy clouds for ways to survive.
you bargained for your life and closed doors from where the sun peeked to stretch it's ray's to you.
â¤
i understand.
it's okay.
â¤
those hands took away so much, so much that should have stayed.
innocence that should have remained untouched, pristine.
happiness should have sprouted from those corners of innocence and joy, from the tenderness of your skin, insteadâ€¦
i see, you grew horns and thorns, spikes and claws.
â¤
i get it.
i feel you.
â¤
all too well.
all too deep.
â¤
but pleaseâ€¦
stop destroying yourself.
â¤
it's been enough you know.
â¤
the hatred, the hurt, the frustrationâ€¦
you have kept imploding.
and all against you.
â¤
you are tired.
i can see.
tired and ready to move forward, to leave that behind, to change your skin.
â¤
ready.
to hug yourself.
to embrace your steps.
to own your heart.
to bless your skin.
â¤
please.
no more.
stop destroying yourself.
i love you.
â¤
come home.
come back.
fully...
â¤
it is safe now.
come hug your body.
come hug your life.
come face existence.
rejoice in the now.
â¤
no hands are pinning you down now.
no eyes are devouring you.
no words or hits are harming you.
â¤
pleaseâ€¦
stop perpetuating what they did to you.
what you learned love was, isn't.
â¤
allow touch to be love again, allow touch to be safe and gentleâ€¦to be welcomed when you are ready to.
come home.
â¤
stop destroying yourself.
come rejoice, come nourish and allow.
come eat and sleep and smile and dream.
â¤
come, come.
come love.
â¤
i love you, rejoice.
come hug life.
let life hug you.
â¤
this body is home, and it's safe to embody and enjoy this existence.
â¤
feel...
it is safe.
allow.
you are safe.
â¤
thank you...for you.
you are home!
i love you.
namaste babe;)

text:
2018 was a banner year for women in politics! 
women candidates broke records for the number of candidates for governor, u.s. house and u.s. senate. and that trend continued in the 2018 midterm elections. 
the u.s. house of representatives elected a record number of women, with at least 90 women expected to make their way to washington, d.c. in january. 
individual candidates also achieved historic firsts. democrats ilhan omar and rashida tlaib became the first muslim women elected to congress. republican marsha blackburn became tennesseeâ€™s first female senator. democrats deb haaland and sharice davids became the first native american women elected to congress. republican kristi noem became south dakotaâ€™s first female governor. -time magazine 
#womeninpolitics #womenleadership #womeningovernment #nastywomen #genderequality #metoo #timesup #womensmarch #womenvote  #womenswave #whyimarch #imarchfor #equality #womensrights  #feminism #feminist #intersectionalfeminism #intersectional #futureisfemale #femaleempowerment #girlsrule #girlsruntheworld #girlboss #ladyboss #ovarygang #girlpower #grlpower #womensupportingwomen

psychologist dr christine blasey ford delivered one of the most powerful testimonies in the #metoo era when she accused supreme court justice brett kavanaugh of sexual assault. she was made to relive a moment that she said "drastically altered" her life, when delivering her testimony in front of a senate judiciary committee consisting of 17 male and four female senators. ford accused kavanaugh of trying to rape her at a high school party some 30 years ago. kavanaugh, who testified after her, forcefully denied the allegation. he was ultimately confirmed in a 50 to 48 vote, with republicans supporting donald trump's pick despite extensive opposition. his nomination inflamed a deep cultural divide in todayâ€™s era of reckoning on sexual assault and harassment. ford and her family became the target of death threats, prompting the launch of a gofundme page to cover their $150,000 security costs. she recently shut down the page after raising nearly $650,000, and has pledged to donate all unused funds to charities that support trauma survivors. #thiswas2018

text:
this is unusual for me... i'm usually posting beautiful pictures i took of the grace found in this world.
i know it's holiday season, i know, 'tis the season to be holly, it's the season of ends and new starts and even mistletoe kisses.
this time, i can't stop thinking about what we still need to improve, i can't stop thinking about the fact that every single day even around the most festive days of the year, there are assaults and abuse happening. and so often, the offenders are people we would not expect to do something like that. the offenders are often people we know, we trust, relatives and friends.
it's enraging thinking about the hurt that many people have to go through every day and the scars they have to carry for the rest of their lives, especially psychical ones.
it was eye opening and a really good start to see the movements of last year and we need to keep going. we need to change the way of thinking, need to show that it's never okay to hurt someone, it's never okay to do something they have not agreed to. we need to show that every person is worth to physical and psychical integrity.
i feel desperate and helpless because of this immense matter and all the structures that even begin in how the children are raised at an early age.
but it has given me hope and strength, this movement and we shall not stop.
there are thousands of thousands of stories... and everyone needs to understand and change (even though i am afraid some people never will). for may this world always be and get better.

text:
.
s h a t t e r  t h e  s i l e n c e .
â¤ï¸
so much here. 
vulnerability. courage. shame. safety.  trust. .
â¤ï¸
from brene brown - "shame is the fear of disconnection - is there something about me that if other people know it or see it that i wonâ€™t be worthy of connection?  for connection to happen we have to allow ourself to be seen. what makes us vulnerable makes us beautifulâ€.
.
â¤ï¸
in brene brownâ€™s ted talk on vulnerability she talks about the meaning of courage.  she states that in latin â€œcorâ€ means heart.  courage is â€œto tell the story of who you are with your whole heart". .
â¤ï¸
forgetting sexual abuse and then starting to remember years later as an adult was the ultimate test of learning to trust myself.  and my body. and learning many lessons around shame, vulnerability, courage, safety, trust, voice, boundaries, patience, self-compassion, self-care and so much more. .
â¤ï¸
interestingly my body "remembered" many years before my mind did. it showed up as physical issues. many authors write about this - babette rothschild, the body remembers.  the body keeps the score, bessel van der kolk.  and more. .
â¤ï¸
there was time for personal inner work. well thatâ€™s on-going, isnâ€™t it!? lower chakra work, throat and heart too.  spiritual growth too comes out of trauma. .
â¤ï¸
so many doubts. so many questions. how could i have forgotten?  yet this is how our bodies help us get through traumatic experiences. disassociating. leaving our body at the time. and then living much of our lives in a similar state. .
disconnected. disembodied. unaware. .

text: too many cases of abuse and assault, sexual or otherwise, go unreported.. this makeup may seem shocking and extreme, but this is what both females and males go through on a daily.. this is their life, pain and fear.. i am a fan of sfx makeup and i want to use my skill and knowledge of it to raise awareness for those people who are in pain.. and yes, not all abuse is visible, it can and is mental and emotional as well as physical.. and physical abuse is most likely to be on other parts of the body, i plan to do work with that as well.. i am here for anyone who needs advice or just to talk.. if you feel in danger of threatened or you go through this, please let someone know, i know it is not easy, i know it is terrifying.. i am someone who went through a sexual assault situation.. and no my experience is not the same as anyone elses. i know that. i'm here to help and to raise awareness.. there are hotlines available 24/7, for example rainn (https://www.rainn.org/about-national-sexual-assault-telephone-hotline) they will help you if you need it.. and so will i. #metoomovement #metoo

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
there is no excuse for sexual abuse. there is no excuse for sexual abuse. there is no excuse for sexual abuse. this is the fifth submission to the survivor tree project (anonymous), and i just want to say to this survivor: i believe you. i do not think you are lying. this was was not your fault. this was not your fault. this was not your fault. â€¢

this woman was abused at a young age by a family member with special needs. there are countless resources available on the topic of recognizing, preventing, and protecting individuals *with* disabilities from sexual abuse. rightfully so- disabled individuals are marginalized and abused at alarmingly high rates, and having these kinds of resources available is absolutely essential. but after i received this story and did some searching, i found that there are not nearly as many readily available resources on what to do if the *abuser* is a disabled individual. itâ€™s a sensitive and multifaceted subject- in many of these cases, the abuser does not understand the concept of consent or of violating anotherâ€™s personal boundaries. but. but. but. this is not an excuse for sexual assault or abuse. an abuserâ€™s disability does not make the abused somehow obligated to put up with inappropriate behavior. in these cases, it is essential that both the abuser *and* the abused get professional intervention, if possible. this woman told her family, and they didnâ€™t believe her. to her, i say: you are valid. you deserve love. you donâ€™t have to go through this alone. get away from those family members, if you can. find a therapist, if you can (itâ€™s confidential, and the best thing i have ever done for myself). if you canâ€™t, you still have options. reach out to the survivor peer support community (see my following list for some helpful ig accounts). call the national sexual assault hotline at 1-800-656-4673, available 24/7/365. you are not alone. âœ¨ğŸŒ± click the link in my bio if others would like to contribute your story to the survivor tree project. #selflove #love #survivor #survivoradvocate #believesurvivors #believewomen #believeblackwomen #rapesurvivor #metoo #timesup #endrapeculture #metoomovement #thesurvivortreeproject #artist

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

trigger warning: rape
what is victim blaming? victim blaming is the idea that a victim was "asking for it" or that it is their fault they were raped. some examples are saying they were drunk or wearing revealing clothes. this is not true, because by definition you cannot ask for rape. it is only ever the fault of the rapist. victim blaming is a way to try to discredit victims and it is never ok.

text:
thank you genx 99.1 for having me
-
this message was to raise awareness about domestic violence but i was detailing what can lead a young girl to end up in a abusive relationship.
-
there are layers to the journey of a girl who doesnâ€™t know about self loves and self worth.
-
it could be from a history of abuse, lack of education about themselves and what to expect as they mature, a lack of positive examples and even a lack of love shown.
-
when you live a life trying to please others due to that lack of self love, our girls will sometimes accept abuse and conform to that personâ€™s needs because they just want to feel some kind of love.
-
young women, never sacrifice who you are to be apart of the crowd or to be in a relationship.
-
it all starts with working on loving yourself. -
there are always signs, you just have to really be present to see.
-

text:
top 9 of 2018. 
what stuck with me: 
wandering around the city with @angiemariel, who always understood my need to run off to get a shot, working a group photo for the attorneys general at the supreme court, photographing polish president andrzej duda, running around capitol hill covering spring events with members of congress, capturing/witnessing some tense moments at gun control and white nationalist rallies, covering the #metoo movement with #survivors and, of course, all the amazing couples who let me shoot their weddings and portrait sessions, who reminded me that despite all of the chaos in our world right now, there will always be love.

text:
if there is anything we can learn from all the sexual abuse that has been exposed over the past few years it is this: 
denying the risk only increases risk. 
the most professional, educated, and likable perpetrators are most likely to be protected by their peers. 
choosing to believe a child and take action to protect them is worth it - every time. it can, literally, save hundreds of lives. 
not educating children about body safety doesnâ€™t protect their innocence, it makes them more vulnerable. 
sexual abuse has been and continues to be an epidemic, that affects all demographics, all institutions, and is still, most common within the family unit with juveniles being one of the biggest segments of perpetrators of child sexual abuse. 
itâ€™s not a matter of *can* we prevent sexual abuse, but if weâ€™re willing.

text:
2018â€™s biggest â€œi canâ€™t believe this happenedâ€ moment - hosting the viatec awards at the royal theatre. for someone with social anxiety, who always considered herself to be shitty at public speaking, struggles with memorization and is not at peace with her body, getting up to host this show in front of 1000 tech industry colleagues, friends and strangers was the most terrifying professional move iâ€™ve made to date. it took a year of events, including grownups read things they wrote as kids, confabulation, my first ever standup comedy set and a fuckup night to get to the point i could stand on a stage and do this. most importantly, i made a statement about our industryâ€™s need for change in the era of #metoo and #timesup that scared the hell out of me and was relieved by the mostly positive reaction. i was fortunate to work with an incredible team from @viatec to support and guide me to ensure all went well. and i think it did. 
overall, it was a lesson in pushing against self-imposed boundaries and going big when it would have been so much easier to say no. so much gratitude tied into all of this for all those who believed in me when i didnâ€™t.

text:
#rp #growtheheckup ğŸ“º planned parenthood is black genocide.

in new york city, thousands more black babies are aborted than born alive each year, and the abortion rate among black mothers is more than three times higher than it is for white mothers. according to a city health department report released in may, between 2012 and 2016 black mothers terminated 136,426 pregnancies and gave birth to 118,127 babies. by contrast, births far surpassed abortions among whites, asians and hispanics.

nationally, black women terminate pregnancies at far higher rates than other women. 
in 2014, 36% of all abortions were performed on black women, who are just 13% of the female population.
.
.

text:
i am beginning the last day of this year in one of my favourite yoga postures - sitting upright in front of my lap top, hands on the keys, steaming cup of tea to the right, ocean view to the left.

i am so struck by the collective voice i have heard and witnessed closing down this year. i donâ€™t remember ever hearing the refrain â€œthank god thatâ€™s overâ€ united so strongly before.  even the mighty in my world - super successful online positivity-get-the-life-you-want-etc giants - are taking time to show the cracks and the wounds and declare 2018 as a year that broke them (of course they are rising now, thank goodness!). as someone who has taken years to identify as a writer simply because i write rather than measuring the validity of this identification by the fame or income connected to it - i am compelled to add my voice.  and yet i find myself hesitating. our natural human urge to share our hearts, to be witnessed and seen feels as though it has been pushed into monstrous distorted shapes these past few years as the exponential speed and reach of online exhibitionism has heated up.  sharing or witnessing another, it all feels so heightened, heated and intense lately.  many of us clamour for attention in the clanging silence of overcrowded noisy virtual spaces. others wait in the shadows, poisoned darts flying from our keyboards, taking advantage of the open vulnerability others are willing to display. 
and so i seek to find my centre and my place in all this.  i remember my feminist mothers (yes i had many) teaching me many years ago - â€œthe personal is the political miraâ€. and so it is.  i believe wholeheartedly in the contradiction that we must take personal responsibility to calm, to centre and to heal knowing full well that the reasons we may be so agitated, un-centred and wounded are in large part the result of the inequities and traumas the collective presses down onto and into us; that while our story is ours alone to own, we only heal in connection with others; that healing may be a quiet private affair or a loud, proud public declaration of what happened or both; that each of us walks our own path but we are undeniably â€œusâ€.
name: the audacious collective

text:
2018 was a one hell of a roller coaster ride. you see, earlier this year and even before i am one of those people who will probably ask sexually assaulted people, why didn't you fought back? why didn't you shouted?

i always remind myself that if it's gonna happen to me i'm gonna fight back. i'm gonna shout at the top of my lungs so i can get everybody's attention.

but on the night of february 24, 2018 i was proven wrong. i stood frozen when some random guy grabbed my boobs out of nowhere. i just stood there for a good minute, legs are so weak it's like they are turning into liquid. i couldn't find the voice to shout, it's like my voicebox disappeared into oblivion, never to come back.

all i could do that time was to dissolved in tears and shook so violently i thought my internal organs will get tangled up with each other.

text:
i've been sitting here thinking about the last 60 days .  i lost a total of 5 family members and friends including my older sister who was just laid to rest less than 2 weeks ago and it hurt bad but i kept going , kept smiling and gave myself permission to grieve when i felt like it was safe .

have you been there ? 
have you ever built a wall that needs to be torn down so that you can authentically connect with people assigned to push you into purpose and build real relationships with ? #metoo 
in my first workbook be b.r.a.v.e , the b=break the ice with other powerful women . and that's hard (at least for me) when you've been hurt & disappointed before but i learned that if you are honest, open and  intentional you'll find purpose & prayer partners ,  confidants & co-laborers in the most unusual places . 
don't dismiss the situation or site of where god wants you to #build again . it's ok to #bebrave , build relationships that will push you to bloom. 
sn-i changed the cover to a more confident , connected me ğŸ™Œ

text:
this photo holds a lot of emotion and has taken me a long time to post. and iâ€™m scared shitless to share. 
the main reason i struggle to post this is because i have people in my life that with have alopecia or are going through chemotherapy and i donâ€™t want it to come across in any way that i am not grateful for my hair.
for me this is something very personal and has been an emotional struggle. a few months back i changed my hair colour and when i sent pictures or people saw me in person, everyone seemed to like it. 
i needed a change as i was about to turn 40 and head back to nashville. for those that have followed me for some time you know that the last three years have been a real tornado. i felt i was marking on a new chapter of my life and wanted change. now i have to note, my stylist did an incredible job and the colour turned out great (in this picture it shows lighter). i wanted red to honour my grandma. 
i had no idea what darkening my hair would do or the triggers it would bring up. 
it was pretty instantly; pretty much the next morning when i awoke and looked in the mirror at the reflection i saw i felt off, distant. 
back in 2012 i cut my hair off for charity and eventually i went blonde and never looked back!
the problem was the marriage i was in was extremely abusive and it seemed to get worse when it came to my appearance. i could only wear certain things, act a certain way, get to a certain size before he was clear what he liked and disapproved of. 
so when he â€œgave me permissionâ€ to cut my hair, it was only expected that after a certain amount of time i was to grow it back out. i continued to cut my hair shorter and his patience grew thin. i was told â€œyou can keep it blonde, though i like it darker; but we had an agreement that you grow it back long. itâ€™s what i prefer.â€ when i eventually left the relationship lets just say my hair became something so precious to me. i shaved the sides one time and continued to cut to short lengths and play with my blonde side. it was so much more than hair; it was an identity that i felt i lost so long ago. crazy as it sounds; blonde feels like home to meğŸ’—

i needed a change as i was about to turn 40 and head back to nashville. for those that have followed me for some time you know that the last three years have been a real tornado. i felt i was marking on a new chapter of my life and wanted change. now i have to note, my stylist did an incredible job and the colour turned out great (in this picture it shows lighter). i wanted red to honour my grandma. 
i had no idea what darkening my hair would do or the triggers it would bring up. 
it was pretty instantly; pretty much the next morning when i awoke and looked in the mirror at the reflection i saw i felt off, distant. 
back in 2012 i cut my hair off for charity and eventually i went blonde and never looked back!
the problem was the marriage i was in was extremely abusive and it seemed to get worse when it came to my appearance. i could only wear certain things, act a certain way, get to a certain size before he was clear what he liked and disapproved of. 
so when he â€œgave me permissionâ€ to cut my hair, it was only expected that after a certain amount of time i was to grow it back out. i continued to cut my hair shorter and his patience grew thin. i was told â€œyou can keep it blonde, though i like it darker; but we had an agreement that you grow it back long. itâ€™s what i prefer.â€ when i eventually left the relationship lets just say my hair became something so precious to me. i shaved the sides one time and continued to cut to short lengths and play with my blonde side. it was so much more than hair; it was an identity that i felt i lost so long ago. crazy as it sounds; blonde feels like home to meğŸ’—

text:
the art of organizing

these past 7 years i've had the honor of working with a lot of community organizers. being tough times there's a lot of issues affecting people and with each issue you see many people stepping up to the plate. like with any other field there's a lot of great organizers, some who shouldn't be in organizing and a rare few who have the passion, tact and determination to bring fellow organizers together for the greater good. 
like with any movement this year we needed a lot of help for the start of #shedoes. that came for us through @carlosthemailman. carlos is no stranger to anyone involved in organizing or politics in la. when it comes to the main issues affecting the people he is always there. not only involved, he brings a ton of help and can bring awareness to your organization or cause. like he did for our #shedoes movement, i've seen him bring solid support to countless other movements in la.

from #housing to #healthcare to #homelessness, #publicbanking, #keepfamiliestogether, helping puerto rico, #metoo, #burlingtonunidos, yes on 10, for our teachers, helping great candidates win, to the front of the fight at #standingrock, carlos has been there. anyone organizing in la knows that if and when you need help, or when you need sound advice, you can always count on carlos.

these last few months were tough for carlos. he was in and out of the hospital. you won't see that on facebook, neither will you see him missing an event where he promised to be there. when others give a million excuses as to why they can't, carlos will always be true to his word. a master in tact and at heart, he is everywhere!

we all know the housing situation in la looks bleak. with rental rates continuing to rise it's affecting everyone. to push the issue to the forefront carlos has organized an amazing march at the rose parade on tuesday the 1st of 2019. things do look bleak for the new year but we have people like carlos fighting for us. he was there for us, now we need to be there for him to fight for fair and affordable housing in la!

#shedoes deserve shelter and protection!

text:
i lived abroad for 2 years, itâ€™s already scary to live alone so far away from home. i couldnâ€™t afford a flat for my self so i shared a room with a guy, he had a girlfriend and the girlfriend also moved in, so i felt kind of safe for a while.
after 1 year, things started to get shady, i missed so many signs, he started to try to control everything in my life, i thought i might be mistaken since the girlfriend was still living there, but then they broke up, he started to control me with fear, i thought he was going to kill me.
i got out of that flat, lucky enough i found another one available, but he kept finding me and following me and trying to intimidate me.
i left the country and came back home. 
i finally feel safe after 6 months. .
.
.

text:
weâ€™re counting down the final hours of 2018 @girledworld and finding many reasons to count the wins for women and girls of the world this year. .

this was the year that saw: â–women across the world unite, stand up and rise to the #metoo and #timesup movements âœ”ï¸
â–an unprecedented number of women speaking out and stepping up to catalyse record-breaking political races and social change âœ”ï¸
â–a series of historic firsts including #spain appointing a majority-women cabinet âœ”ï¸
â–voters in ireland striking down one of the most draconian #abortion bans in the developed world âœ”ï¸
â–women in saudi arabia able to drive legally âœ”ï¸
â–female candidates breaking historic ground in the us midterm elections and @michelleobama findjng her powerful voiceâœ”ï¸
â–iranian women watching the #worldcup in a sports stadium alongside men for the first time âœ”ï¸
â–new zealand prime minister #jacindaardern making history as the second elected head of state to give birth while in office, and first elected leader ever to take maternity leave proving it is indeed possible to be both a prime minister and mum âœ”ï¸âœ”ï¸
â–the #nobelpeace prize awarded jointly to denis mukwege, a congolese surgeon who treats rape victims, and nadia murad, an iraqi woman and member of the yazidi religious minority who was captured by isis and is now an activist advocating for victims of sex trafficking, and the first iraqi woman to receive the award âœ”ï¸ .
â– and among countless other extraordinary ordinary moments of women and girls standing up, stepping up and speaking out, without knowing it possibly, without claiming it, so too, they have advanced the causes, opportunities and rights of all women and girls, and in their honour, we @girledworld would like to thank them and thank you for being part of what made our 2018 rock, and leave you with the powerful wisdom of @drmayaangelou to give you fuel for 2019. .

text:
i was planning on making a really cliche â€œend of 2018â€ post about growth and finishing school etc, but i learnt something today that has changed my mind. iâ€™m not going to sit here and blab about how thankful i am for everything because the truth is iâ€™m not. there are a lot of things that i am not grateful for, some of which i refuse to stay quiet about any longer. iâ€™m not grateful that i left wangaratta high school 18 months ago and people are still telling lies/believing lies about me. so iâ€™m here to tell my truth and set the record straight. today i learnt that a certain individual (if youâ€™re familiar with this story youâ€™ll know who iâ€™m talking about) has been telling people that the reason that we are no longer talking is because i blamed all of my problems on other people. to be perfectly honest, heâ€™s partly correct; i did blame some of my problems on him. the reason for this, however, is that my problem was trying to cope with being sexually assaulted, and i blamed him because he was the one who did it. i donâ€™t care if no one believes me anymore. anyone who still thinks this is my fault and believes his bullshit lies please feel free to unfollow me/never talk to me again because i donâ€™t want people like you in my life anymore. and iâ€™m not afraid to say it anymore because it isnâ€™t my fault. i didnâ€™t ask for it; quite the opposite actually, and i have nothing to be ashamed of.
to end this on a cliche iâ€™m incredibly grateful for my gal pals for sticking by me and always believing (in) me. you girls are incredible and i love you so much. happy end of 2018 and thanks for coming to my tedtalk #metoo

text:
#confession of 2018: since everyone only share happy events of their lives and their accomplishments, i thought to share my failures or at least one failure which defined most of my 2018 in a good way (or at least i think it is good). so in 2017, friends and family talked me out of my major apprehensions regarding relationships and i decided that yes, i wonâ€™t mind getting married. getting a green signal, a friend quickly introduced me to someone, i liked him and we immediately started going out. for first few months, everything was happy and amazing but at the end of 2017, everything turned bad. i was going through hell at work, as my the-then boss was making the workplace extremely uncomfortable for me and i took a stand by speaking about it (yes, #metoo). under duress, i was having emotionally weak moments and i had a minor accident too. while i was going through all of that, i realised that he wasnâ€™t there, as someone who actually should have been there. fine that i am an independent woman and i have lived alone and i can handle shit but then why would i need to be with someone if i canâ€™t count on him in my weak moments and/or i would need to think so much to just make a call or drop a message to that person, do i need him? with this thought, i entered 2018 and the first thing i did in 2018 was to sort that mess. i said goodbye to him. the efforts he made in the following days were enough consolation for me for taking that decision. i wonâ€™t lie, there were times when i got weaker and/or i thought i am being egotistic and i dropped him a text. thankfully, it didnâ€™t work but what made me realise was that i need to hold all of them close to my heart who have been there, despite my shortcomings. i made a conscious effort to stay in touch with them and be thankful to them or i apologised to them if and when there was a need. i stopped people from taking me for granted. and so on and so forth.
.
.
.
this â€˜equilibrist on one armâ€™ by jorge marist, displayed at the hyder aliyev center is a true depiction of my life in 2018. i have grown to be so different today that i can look at any kind of danger in the eye. i am ready to embrace 2019. #happynewyear
name: Maria Patel

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
a year in review would not be complete without a mention of illinois senator tammy duckworth.  this spring, duckworth, 50, became the first senator to give birth while in office. on april 18, senators voted unanimously to allow infants on the floor during votes, reversing a rule that prohibited family members. that same day, duckworth brought her 10-day-old daughter, maile pearl bowlsbey, as she voted against confirming james bridenstine as nasaâ€™s next administrator. 
having a baby at 50 shows you canâ€™t have it all.  i had my kids later in life because i made the choice early in my career that women shouldn't to have to make. i was in my 20s and trying to rise through the ranks of the military, i knew if i took time off to get pregnant and raise my children, it would limit my career. when theyâ€™re climbing the ladder, so many young women have to make this decision. they go on the mommy track because we donâ€™t have the structures in place to support them. 
one support is paid family leave.  duckworth is cosponsoring senator kirsten gillibrandâ€™s [d-ny] bill. itâ€™s based on kind of an insurance model, where you would contribute the equivalent of $2.50 a week and it would provide 12 weeks of paid family leave. and the employer would pay $3 a week. itâ€™s very reasonable, itâ€™s self-directed, itâ€™s people helping themselves, and it just makes sense. 
on the cusp of being passed is the friendly airports for mothers (fam) act.  the fam act would require all medium and large airports, which would be over 90 percent of the airports in this country, to provide safe lactation rooms for moms. -marie claire

these are solutions that are both fair and make sense.  good things are happening!  we can't wait to hear her next great ideas!  #womeninpolitics #womenleadership #womeningovernment #nastywomen #genderequality #metoo #timesup #womensmarch #womenvote #womenswave #whyimarch #imarchfor #equality #womensrights #feminism #feminist #intersectionalfeminism #intersectional #futureisfemale #femaleempowerment #girlsrule #girlsruntheworld #girlboss #ladyboss #ovarygang #girlpower #grlpower #womensupportingwomen #eeoc #diversity

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
manasi pradhan is an author and poet who received the rani lakshmibai stree shakti puraskar in 2013 for her work in fighting for women rights. born to a poor family in the state of odisha, she travelled 15 km daily to the only school in the entire region. she was the first woman from her village to earn a law degree. she has won many accolades including the â€˜outstanding women awardâ€™ in 2011 from the united nationâ€™s un women and national commission for women. she is the founder of nirbhaya vahini and oyss women and head the honour for women national campaign, a nationwide movement to end violence against women in india. she is also serving on the panel of central board of film certification (censor board) for india. she is a member of the international governing council of world women organization (wwo) and inquiry committee of the national commission for women. she was awarded with the stree shakti puraskar in 2013 by the former president mr pranab mukherjee.
.
.
in 2014, the honour for women national campaign headed by manasi pradhan released a four-point charter of demand for all state governments of india:

1. complete clamp down on liquor trade
2. self-defense training for women as part of educational curriculum
3. special protection force for women security in every district
4. fast-track court and special investigating & prosecuting wing for crime against women in every district. the charter forms a cornerstone of the movement and has led several state governments to make suitable amendments.
.
she is an inspiration for many and a role model for all of us.
. 
sources: yourstory & wikipedia

text:
the year ends with a warm meal and a fine book to read. what more could a girl want!

reflecting on the year that went by, i see a lot of positive events that have happened. the dilution of section 377, the fury of #metoo movement, the criminalising of triple talaq among many other. although the critiques might point out to me that there have been a high number of disastrous events too and i duly acknowledge it, but we cannot fail to recognise the history that is being made and the huge turn of events that has been happening to help progress humanity.

forgive me, if i want to end this year on a happier note and believe in the fact that 2018 has been a good year, that there still resides kindness in us, that the marginalised sections of this society will receive their dues, that education and food and shelter will reach one and all and that we have hope of saving humankind.

text:
hey 2018, wanna know what you taught me? you taught me i still have a crush on chewbacca and also a new one on james comey.
_
you taught me that the world is filled with intelligent, conscious and positive people, who live with truth and hope. 
_
you taught me that when you literally and figuratively fall, you get up to become stronger, happier and feeling pretty kick ass. 
_
you taught me that my uno game is truly better than ever!!
_
you taught me that thereâ€™s a seemingly endless myriad of self-absorbed jerks in the world - and that in stark contrast to this, it is the conscious, selfless and positive people on which iâ€™m focused and to whom i tip my metaphorical hat. 
_
you taught me how much i love my family. 
_
you taught me to remain the antithesis of hyperbole. 
_
you taught me how much i still love coffee. 
_
and finally, youâ€™ve taught me that tonight, i will drink my body weight in champagne. 
_
happy new year to the non-jerks out there!! i hope 2019 brings you more love, more positivity and more dogs on beaches!
_

text:
with 2018 nearing to an end, i felt like this was something everybody should hear and believe. 2018 has been a crazy year, no doubt. i've had my ups and downs but with 2019 looming ahead, i can safely say that i managed to get through all the pain and the joy that this year has brought me. at the moment, most things seemed like the end of the world and i could not think past that one failure but, now looking back on it, it feels like just another conundrum amidst many. i'm proud of myself for standing my ground through all that and i feel everyone else should be equally proud for living through another messy year. 2018, while, somewhat pain inducing, has also been a year where social movements have progressed rapidly and that's something to be joyful about. so many rape victims have come forward to claim justice, transgenders were finally given identity cards in pakistan, women were issued driving licenses in saudi arabia. with so much more hope for these movements, 2019 can only bring an even more rapid progress and change. happy new year!
.
. .
.
.
.
.
.
#feminism #feminist #womenempowerment #powertothewomen #girlpower #unabashedlyshameless #newyear #pain #joy #hopeful #change #2019 #justice #metoo #socialmovements #loveyourself #happynewyear

i am a daughter, i am a sister, i am a cousin, i am a friend, i am a women, i am... en un abrir y cerrar de ojos lo que antes era musa ahora es objeto, lo que antes era templo ahora es sexo. tu ves desnudes, yo veo arte.  la cantidad de ropa que tengo no define la cantidad de respeto que merezco. muchos miran pero no ven. y ahi viene el problema que ha pasado desde el comienzo de nuestra existencia, donde la humanidad piensa que tiene el derecho de criticar, abusar, herir, maltratar solo por lo que tengo o por lo que ven. cansa tener que caminar por las calles con miedo, tener que velar lo que me pongo, digo, pienso, porque provocÃ³ o te insulta, cansa tener que velar donde salgo, con quien, y la hora, porque hay mas gente que quiere hacer mas mal que bien, cuando debe de haber mas gente que haga el bien y no el mal. cansa tener que ver en las redes, noticias, periÃ³dicos, mundo, de personas que fueron matadas, maltratadas y violadas.
cansa tener que vivir con la mirada de que soy carne en vez de que soy diosa. ojo, esto no significa que hay que vivir sin malicia, al contrario, la malicia tiene que ser la base. pero el problema no es mi ropa, el problema es tu mentalidad. el problema no es mi traje muy corto o muy largo, es tu forma de sexualizar, el problema no es que me lo busque, es tu atrevimiento de faltarme el respeto, el problema no soy yo, eres tu. el problema no es la mujer ni el hombre que pasan por esta situaciÃ³n, es que la sociedad desea hechar la culpa, hacer silencio, dar la otra cara y hacer que no vio nada.

text:
2018 has been a very interesting year. lots of ups and downs yet i feel like i've truly grown as a person and with my business. some major highlights - got to visit paris and amsterdam with @sreenag and @gearheadvyx. this break was much needed and was unforgettable. worked with aweosme clients like @dakshinachitra_heritagemuseum @kalpanarts @srinivasan2728 @chennaiphotobiennale @playadishakti to name just a few. got to visit telengana weavers and really see all the magic happen thanks to @narasimhanvenkatesh. visited for the first time @zeejlf, started the #margazhi updates blog and probably the biggest highlight for me is pulling off the #metoo themed #golu. each year i wonder how i'm going to outdo the previous one but some how it all works out thanks to @sreenag @sajjige @nagarajanroopa @brramkumar so.. fingers crossed! happy new year everybody!
. .
.
.
.
#happynewyear #2019 #yearahead #entrepreneurlife #girlboss #entrepreneurship #entrepreneur
