text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

domestic violence survivors can face ongoing and challenging effects after enduring physical, mental, and emotional abuse. it can take time for a survivor to adjust to living in a safe environment, especially if a perpetrator was severely violent and/or committed the actions over an extended period of time.
while addressing this pain can be overwhelming, the healing process can help survivors develop inner strengths and lessen their fear of safety for themselves and their families. on the journey to recovery, survivors and those who support them should understand thatÂ healing takes time. the effects of this trauma can vary widely person to person due to individualsâ€™ responses to stress, age, and the frequency and severity of abuse.
.

text:
it's not the waking it's the rising. 
every small word, deed or action of resistance against this system, helps, echos, reaches others. is a light.

it can be defeated. we can end patriarchy & rape culture & the oppression of so many.

to survivors.. i hope you heal & find comfort in feminism, therapy, friendship. i'm not sure closure is possible, it's definitely a journey, but there is solidarity & support & if you have to write it on your bedroom mirror - it was not your fault. be gentle & kind to yourself as you would a friend. i know you are strong, but it's ok to be vulnerable too. x

to people who care.. listen. believe survivors, trust them, respect them. there is no humanity in the justice system no room for the emotional & rape or assault are highly emotive topics. people are allowed to deal with their experience in their own way. there is no 'wrong' or 'right'. where possible attend marches, sign petitions, show support, be an ally. speak out when you can, whether sharing a link or challenging a friend on a comment at a party or in the office.

if you are safe & in a position to do so, where you do not fear for your safety.. & you feel able to do so.. please try & challenge people on problematic comments, language or action. "if you are neutral in situations of injustice, you have chosen the side of the oppressor" (i have no problem with people not feeling able to speak out if they feel vulnerable, psychologically, unwell, or in a potentially unsafe situation - but i feel privileged allys - usually straight white men, rarely have an excuse for their silence in the face of injustice apart from not wanting to upset the apple cart, or challenge a friend which is so cowardly & normalises the language & actions that encourage entitlement & disrespect that leads to assault & rape to continue). #metoo #feminism #endrapeculture #consent #respect #ibelieveher #letboyscry #endgenderstereotypes #endviolence #boyswillbeheldaccountablefortheiractions #standwithsurvivors #rise #solidarity

text:
2018 is drawing to a close, and it is time for us to look back on the past year and what weâ€™ve achieved in it. our team grew from three full time members to four full time members, while our hindi editor stayed on as a part time member. our team now includes japleen pasricha â€“ founder-director, asmita ghosh â€“ campaign manager, swati singh â€“ hindi editor, amudha mv â€“ content editor and suman saurav â€“ digital editor. we also shifted offices this year to take up a small space in a building in naraina vihar, new delhi.

with our little team growing in size slowly but surely, so is the impact of our work. our average monthly website hits doubled, and our social media following rose as well! our writer family grew by over a 100 people, and we also had the distinct pleasure of significantly increasing the number of writers from marginalized positions, making our content more reflective of diverse sociopolitical identities.

we ran several successful campaigns this year, both in-house and in partnership with organizations whose work we admired. in-house campaigns drew on our followersâ€™ experiences and amplified them, while partnered campaigns boosted valuable work that social good organizations had been doing. inÂ #chalkfullbullying, we highlighted stories of gender-based bullying in schools, while inÂ #unsanskarilove, we spotlighted unconventional love stories and how difficult it is for queer, inter-caste or inter-faith love to survive in india. 
our #didyouask campaign anticipated the second wave of the #metoo movement, in which we used thought provoking videos created byÂ pld indiaÂ to spark a conversation on navigating consent and handling rejection. our instagram stories saw many deeply personal incidents being, where followers resonated with the snippets in the video and added their own thoughts to it, leading to a highly enriching conversation. theÂ #unstereotypecinemaÂ campaign in partnership withÂ oxfam indiaÂ was also a major conversation starter, where we unpacked the patriarchal biases in our favourite indian films and spoke about how cinema systematically objectifies and dehumanizes women.

with our little team growing in size slowly but surely, so is the impact of our work. our average monthly website hits doubled, and our social media following rose as well! our writer family grew by over a 100 people, and we also had the distinct pleasure of significan notly increasing the number of writers from marginalized positions, making our content more reflective of diverse sociopolitical identities.

we ran several successful campaigns this year, both in-house and in partnership with organizations whose work we admired. in-house campaigns drew on our followersâ€™ experiences and amplified them, while partnered campaigns boosted valuable work that social good organizations had been doing. inÂ #chalkfullbullying, we highlighted stories of gender-based bullying in schools, while inÂ #unsanskarilove, we spotlighted unconventional love stories and how difficult it is for queer, inter-caste or inter-faith love to survive in india. 
our #didyouask campaign anticipated the second wave of the #metoo movement, in which we used thought provoking videos created byÂ pld indiaÂ to spark a conversation on navigating consent and handling rejection. our instagram stories saw many deeply personal incidents being, where followers resonated with the snippets in the video and added their own thoughts to it, leading to a highly enriching conversation. theÂ #unstereotypecinemaÂ campaign in partnership withÂ oxfam indiaÂ was also a major conversation starter, where we unpacked the patriarchal biases in our favourite indian films and spoke about how cinema systematically objectifies and dehumanizes women.

text: i started my year as a feminist in residence @projectforemptyspace and debuted lnteriors: we are all pink inside (and am so happy that 2019 will start with a group show that includes the installation) and am so grateful to @rjampol and @browngirlcurator - i had so many great moments @projectforemptyspace this year. (thatâ€™s where i got the â€œfuck you pay meâ€ shirt! ) iâ€™m still in remission! thatâ€™s a big yay and wow and grateful to be alive and have a little family with @mckenziewark3000 . i published a few things- about @catalinacruzny and @ifpfilm - ifp was a huge part of my 2018 and surprised it didnâ€™t show up here, their support for my film project is huge. my high school started to face itâ€™s reckoning about abuses. i taught what is rape culture? , the body in performance art, and rape culture and sexual justice. i painted dicks. i danced. lots of failures too- still have done that last edit on my book project, i havenâ€™t been able to write to my school to ask for what i want them to do, i got rejected from many, many grants and a big institutional thing that i really thought was going to happen, didnâ€™t. iâ€™ve been slow to process some emotions, and got really fucked up by the kavanaugh hearings. iâ€™m still working on my internal white supremacy and internalized patriarchy. i still want to â€œwinâ€ even though i know thereâ€™s no winning. iâ€™ve found hope in this shitshow. friends were surprised i wasnâ€™t more vocal about #metoo and i havenâ€™t been in touch with my family in canada and buffalo much. iâ€™m still healing, but finally feeling much stronger. hereâ€™s to love and creativity and tenderness and vulnerabily in 2019. also, why was there no option to save the mother in bandersnatch?

text:
walking into the new year with my best girlfriend â€” my daughter. 
this has been an important year for many women around the world. whatever criticisms #metoo movement deserves, it also helped many women (and men) to speak up, to process their trauma and to feel more entitled to not be subjected to abuse and exploitation. raising a young girl, becoming aware of and healing my own traumas, all have been aided by this big debate. yes, papers try to turn everything into the usual money-making media circus, but personally i found a lot of reassurance and support from what was happening on a global scale. finding oneâ€™s own sacred physical emotional mental and spiritual integrity that shouldnâ€™t be interfered with or compromised in work and other circumstances and teaching the same to my daughter â€” this is one of the biggest themes of 2018 for me. 
the other side of the coin, of confronting those who donâ€™t respect the physical or psychological boundaries of other humans, is how we project ourselves to the world. in everyday life and on social media. sex sells, but if we really care about ourselves and our children and want to be part of the bigger wave of change thatâ€™s happening in global consciousness, we have to confront ourselves and reflect on how we are contributing to this issue with our own behavior. iâ€˜ve been trapped in a narcissistic selfie culture of social media for at least one year and a half it was enough to realize how toxic and damaging it is to oneâ€™s soul. while i love seeing photographs of people i follow here, thereâ€™s a fine line between sharing your being and energy on an occasional basis or a daily obsession of trying to sell yourself through never-ending stream of selfies. i cannot comment on fashion industry that basically is based on sexualized images, but to see intelligent women, writers, poets, artist, actors, yogis who project themselves like cheap models and seem to be totally lost in their own narcissistic ego is painful. letâ€™s not encourage it here, letâ€™s speak up against it & help each other overcome this disease of the soul. this is our responsibility in the #metoo movement: to re-write the rules of the game that belongs to the past.

text:
wow. what a year. so many highs and plenty of lows. this year i built relationships with family members i'd never even met. my dad, my grandmother, aunties, uncles, cousins... people who i will cherish and love dearly for the rest of my life. i spent 8 hard weeks training for my first mma fight and won with pride. i was broke at times. some days i didn't even want to be here. i was homeless and then housed all in the space of 3-4 months. i lost people. whether they passed away, went to jail or even just disappeared. i've watched long term friends grab life by the horns and break down barriers against all odds. i've seen others crumble under the weight of every day life. i sat in court every day for a week to eventually watch a man get sent down for the destruction he inflicted upon people i love, and then i watched those loved ones triumph in piecing themselves back together. my friends have inspired me to do and be better, not just after the clock strikes twelve but always. every day. in the new year i'll be granted with some funding for my music and words can't describe how excited i am to get the ball rolling again. i'm proud of my family and how far we've come. i'm proud of all my friends who overcame addiction and who spoke out about mental health. all my sisters who spoke out when the #metoo hashtag came into play, i'm proud of you for your strength and honesty. and so i'd like to wish each and every one of you a happy new year. thank you for supporting me. thank you for believing in what i do and thank you for getting this far into my essay without falling asleep.

lest be said, this year has been a bloody whirlwind. but none of my achievements would be at all credible if i didn't have my stunning fiancÃ© by my side through it all. so this year my darling, is to you. to us. we deserve all the fun and joy 2019 brings and more. my life partner. i love you kiddo â¤ï¸

planners and journals! they have everything you know you need and everything you haven't thought of, jam packed inside.

see you all in 2019!

remember tonight: "consent is everything" & no one is consenting to being on the road with drunk drivers. so please call an uber, a friend or hop on transit.

text: 2018 has brought with it a lot of change- some i was ready for and some that was thrust upon me (#metoo). 2018 was my last year in nyc but it was also my first red carpet in la. 2018 brought with it my first time directing, my first time buying a car, and my first time being in a wedding. i spent far too much time in 2018 dealing with drunk idiots, pouring foamy beer, and building upon my overall distaste for the general public. but i also spent much of 2018 surrounded by some incredibly funny human beings that made those days & nights worth it. and while 2018 didnâ€™t bring me many auditions, i started my career as a content creator. i said hello to new hair and goodbye to my sweet girl lily. 2018 didnâ€™t feel like a remarkable year to me until i went back to do this #2018in12photos. and then i saw all the wondrous adventures i have been fortunate for this year. thank you to this year for teaching me what my definition of success truly is. thank you 2018 for revealing to me my shadow and for giving me a chance to find the courage to journey within that cave. i look forward- always - to every moment i am lucky enough to call myself alive. see you in la, 2019! âœŒğŸ»ğŸŒ

text:
2018 was a year of ups and downs but it was definitely a year of history-making moments for women all around the world. here are just few things we accomplished:
1ï¸âƒ£women broke records in elections all over the world from the record number of female candidates elected to the u.s house of representatives to spain's female-majority cabinet even here in lebanon where we saw a record number of women on the ballot. an unprecedented 113 women registered as candidates, and 86 of them made it to candidate lists. this was a whopping increase from 2009, when only 12 women candidates had registered.
2ï¸âƒ£in saudi arabia, women were finally given the legal right to drive
3ï¸âƒ£the usa gymnastics team found their voices and stood up to their abuser.
4ï¸âƒ£movies with strong female leads ruled the box office.
5ï¸âƒ£nadia murad, a yazidi woman who was captured by isis, won the nobel peace prize
6ï¸âƒ£film producer harvey weinstein arrives at manhattan criminal court in new york. weinstein was one of the first men accused of sexual misconduct in the #metoo movement
7ï¸âƒ£christine blasey ford, a california college professor, accused then-supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh of sexual assaulting her in high school 
8ï¸âƒ£britainâ€™s prince harry  broke the british rules by marrying american actress meghan markle.

text:
2018 brought on a collective shift in consciousness. it also revealed the illusion of separation in heartbreaking ways. the duality of right + wrong and left + right are designed to keep us down. 
ğ–¥³
this was very apparent with the #metoo movement and rising of the feminist movement, which i have been a part of. hereâ€™s the thing- when itâ€™s not done in balance, itâ€™s actually a masculine approach to bringing down the patriarchy. the #divinefeminine is truly rising when it honors the #divinemasculine. when there is man bashing and hate of any kind, itâ€™s only creating more separation.  when we create space for men to get in touch with their emotions and express them, we are healing. 
ğ–¥³
as someone who came forward and told my truth about (some) of the sexual abuse iâ€™ve experienced, i have to say that the most healing part of my journey was forgiving the men who acted out of their suffering when they abused me.  forgiveness released all the shame i was carrying around unknowingly. 
ğ–¥³
forgiveness creates compassion. my intent in 2019 is to take aligned, compassionate action to continue shifting the collective out of the illusion of separation. itâ€™s incredible how many people are waking up right now. 2018 showed me that itâ€™s possible to bring balance back on earth. 
ğ–¥³
my wish for 2019 is for everyone to experience our true nature of oneness, of divine love, of whatever name you call it. much love and all the light. ğŸ’—kat

text: 2018 - blessed, happy, powerful and free. passion, love, luck and joy. best time of my life. fell in love with canada and built a new home there. the start of a new, exciting chapter. intersectional feminist empowerment. sisters raising together and supporting each other #metoo #niunamas. losing hope and regaining it every other day, quite a weird feeling but it balanced out in the end. new lessons learned and old, wrong lessons forgotten. lots of good books. played my fav jams 24/7 and counting. discovered country music and whisky. a lot of hip hop too. quality memes brought to you by millennials and gen z. yummy food as often as needed, special thanks go to chocolate, cookies, sushi and padthai. congrats, vegan food! you kinda changed my ways. pizza didn't make it to the list this year, but it's still part of my soul. poutine, you were up there. new perspectives and philosophies. amazing buds and pals. finally visited la and vancouver. many mind blowing parties and after parties. lots of cool people i got to know and miss. moments that will be forever treasured. a shit ton of knowledge about sustainability and social and environmental responsibility. mental health awareness. self-love, self-care, body positivity, gym and pampering days. setting new goals and fighting for them. let's wrap up this pretty dope year. 2018, you did better than good. 2019, you're on! show me what you got â¤ cheers ğŸ»

happy new year! - for me iâ€™ll be the big 51 in one week. for the new year and a more â€œauthenticâ€ me (hate that word but using it anyhow) iâ€™ve gone back to my natural color red. well, auburn is more like it but iâ€™m working it a little brighter this time around after being blonde for the past 25 years. iâ€™ve had several people tell me they donâ€™t like it, which is funny because i never asked their opinion and donâ€™t care. you would think some would know me by now or at least get my â€œi donâ€™t give ağŸ’©â€ vibe. ğŸ˜ to all who walk the path less paved, donâ€™t listen to anyone but the voice inside your soul. donâ€™t allow any outer negativity to cause you to be afraid of who you are or second guess what you know to be true in your heart. donâ€™t be afraid to stand out and stand up for what you believe in. and ladies, speak kindly of others, stay away from drama and rumors and only speak the truth. in this day and age iâ€™m seeing and hearing a lot of negativity towards each other and men and this is the time to use #girlpower and the #metoo movement with kindness, care and responsibility. not as a means of retribution and control. .
.
.

text:
happy new year everyone! this was my 2018. going through these, i'd forgotten that half of the stuff happened just this year!! it has been an adventurous year of travel both for business and pleasure to massachusetts, orlando, and salt lake city. 
i got to walk with the @womensmarchnyc expressing the love i have for my country.
i got to see so many of my loved ones perform, friends get married, and new films be produced.
it's been a magical potter filled year with some of the most incredible friends. i saw @hpplayus twice and got to meet some of the cast, went to @nyhistory and got to see jkr's original sketches and plans of the potter books, finally went to @comicconnyc, saw an early premiere of @crimesofgrindelwald, and went to @harrypotteruniversal! 
and at the start of this year, my first short @innocencefilm2017  premiered at @iffnyfestival and won best short film and continued to win awards in excellence the rest of the year. (news on streaming release soon to come! ğŸ¬) i am so beyond grateful for my experiences of this year. putting it all together reminds me to not sweat the small things and to love the adventure of life surrounded by my loved ones. on to 2019!

now what do you want to accomplish in 2019?  do your goals align with your greater purpose?  when you have clarity on your â€œwhyâ€œ you will find it easier to be motivated every day to accomplish your goals.

once you have your purpose- aligned goals, write them down in detail and imagine yourself accomplishing these goals as if theyâ€™ve already happened.

donâ€™t second-guess your goals comparing yourself to someone who may be further along. remember, these are your goals and not anyone elseâ€™s.

think of yourself as a blank canvas and each brush stroke is a goal moving towards your beautiful painting of your purpose.  donâ€™t worry about the final artwork, just keep painting. 
and any rejection you might receive now, just turn it into fuel.  prove them wrong.  remember you are living your purpose and no one can stop you.

and if you temporarily fall off track you donâ€™t need to wait until january 1st every year to start over. every day is the perfect day to get back on track or start something new!  you are unstoppable! 
iâ€™m sending you love, good health and happiness for 2019!  happy new year! cheers! xo

text:
yo yo everybody! happy new year! my name is kerilyn russo. you can find me at  @thisdreamergirl here on instagram.
.
the amazing @jenpastiloff invited me to takeover this account today, on my 44th birthday and well, can you tell iâ€™m excited (maybe more nervous, letâ€™s be real, i was shaking as i did this video.)
.
a little about me. i am a dreamer, a sensitive soul, a mama (honestly the best title i have at the moment) i am a believer of the teachings of a course in miracles - i have my own #metoo experience that i have never felt safe enough to share publicly, i know so many of you do too. i am a certified life coach, although currently that title doesnâ€™t resonate.
.
i am a teacher and a student.
.
not one without the other.
.
i have been learning through experience about #codependency and #narcissism and i am now here here to remind you,
.
you are not alone.
.
just today, i have heard from three different women who have had to flee a scary situation and if you are reading this, please know,
.
you are strong.
you can be trusted.
.
you are not crazy. 
and again,
.
you are not alone. *you hear me?
.
so i have three more posts to share, and an offer at the end to work with me (learning to trust my inner #bossbabe ) i am giddy to share with you all iâ€™m learning.
.
happy new year to you all who happen to stop scrolling on this video. away we go.
.

women of color self-defense scholarship program now open
_____
the past couple years have been challenging for women, communities of color and lgbtq+ folks. recently weâ€™ve seen increased incidents that may have undermined our sense of safety: attacks on immigrants and the lgbtq community, #metoo reports of epidemic sexual harassment and assault for women in all sectors, as well as a rise in intimate partner violence. safety continues to be a growing concern for many marginalized people. but we are also taking a stand and fighting back, helping each other, and in many cases triumphing as we did during the midterm elections with historic wins for women of color. 
_____
as jiu-jitsu martial artists, we are joining the fight by offering our knowledge to empower and strengthen our community. starting in 2019, sweaty betties and @fourelementsfitness will be joining forces to help end violence against women and girls, particularly among girls and women of color with low to modest means. we are collaborating to offer scholarships to a monthly womenâ€™s self-defense workshops. our goal is to provide free self-defense training for girls and women at four elements fitness in oakland, ca. 
____
sponsorship application for the february womenâ€™s self-defense workshop is open now and the deadline is jan.25. 2019. scholarships are first come, first served basis with limited amount per month. must be girls or women of color and ages 9+ to apply. no experience required to attend workshop. we reserve the right to close applications when full capacity are reached. if you or anyone you know are interested in a life-changing opportunity, please contact us at mollii@fourelementsfitness.com. workshop details below:

text:
#24speciesofcrane project interim update

today the team was enjoying @kfc's all new vegan zinger burger with a side of that #veganbeef burrito from @tacobell yu quiero's and delicious orange julius's to slurp it all down. is it julius', juliuses, julius's, or juliusii?Â  anyways, we were amazing at the quality and flavor of organic vegan food that these big chains are able to produce and at >80% organic food, it's pretty good even for a stay at home vegan with convienient access market farms.

now that the scene has been set, a #shocking discovery was made recently by our research team. while examining crane feet, they noticed that while cranes feet are not webbed, ducks feet are. in addition to this newfoundland retrievers have webbed feet. this information totally blows the longstanding theory that crane dna was used in retrieving dogs to help them travel in wetlands, and points the finger a the duck. this makes sense as all of these purpose built killing machines are somehow magnetically drawn to ducks. this whole genetic modification thing knows no bounds. we now have factual evidence to suggest the whooping crane was forcibly bred with the dachshund to create the modern day grey hound, a bloody thirsty frankenstein of a dog that will chase a rabbit until they kill it.

it grosses us out when companies resort to #gmo and #breeding and worst of all selective reprodution to achieve increase farm efficiencies and better tasting healthier food. just look at the apple and corncob in the year 3000bc, pathetic really in size, and totally flavorless and hard, and now they are big juicy frankenfruits packed with vitamins we haven't even bothered to educate ourselves on because deep down we know that anything with omega 3 is fish, and we still love tomatoes but refuse to eat the flesh of another living being because we are all people.

so anyways, after a short break for the holiday period we will be back with the last remaining cranes just in time for hindu new years and some exciting news about life after the crane campaign. 
in the mean time, go #creaseforpeace

#origami @peta #notmypresident #trump2020 #cranesarepeople #lgbtqc #metoo #cranestoo #flatearth

text:
two years ago, we flew to memphis, tennessee, to spend a couple of days in "the south" during my winter break. 
it felt like a good idea at the time, especially since we had never spent new year's eve in the u.s. and the southern states promised to be a lot warmer than germany. but traveling in winter, as we learned -- and i should have remembered from a traumatic flight that involved a miniature prop plane, a snow storm, and a stranger whose fear of airplanes caused him to constantly clasp my thigh for moral support (#metoo, but also #propplanesaretheworst) --, follows its own rules. 
we got stuck in heathrow on the way to memphis (minneapolis and paris on the way back) and really struggled with the jetlag because of the delay. he then caught a man cold, i caught a legitimate cold, and both began to feel depressed because we had to do research on a story on emmett till (if you don't know, look it up, you'll understand). the fact that the presidential election had only happened two months ago didn't help either: some people were still visibly in shock, some people proudly donned their bumper stickers, but most people were just walking on eggshells. 
by new year's eve we were so exhausted that we sought shelter at a small but very cute thai restaurant in memphis. as we were the only customers, the elderly woman running the place buzzed with excitement and brought us plate after plate -- some of which we had ordered, some of which we had not but which, we thought, she wanted us to taste because, after all, this was new year's and maybe there were some good people left on this planet.

when the check arrived we not only had had the best mango sticky rice of our lives, but also one of the most expensive meals ever (and we have, by now, traveled to hawaii). we looked, incredulously, at the handwritten numbers on the bill, looked, incredulously, at each other, and then 
started laughing. 
was it overpriced? yes. 
was it worth it? yes. 
we payed, thanked her, drove to the hotel, went to bed at eight, and made the new year's resolution to never, ever again travel during this time of the year. 
happy new year. 
#travelgram #travelstories #memphis #happy2019

text:
as another year around the sun concludes, i find myself reflecting on my past 28 years and how i want to spend my final year before undeniable adulthood.  i want to let go of any shame iâ€™ve been harboring about my past and be free to enter into a new year fresh.

four years ago, in the close of 2014,  i had my first experience with methamphetamine, and for the following year i experimented and abused the drug periodically (about 4 times in the course of the year). i lived so long in a deep depression and with heavy anxiety that i had stopped feeling all together, and crystal was a way to feel again.  so when i used, i used hard and carelessly.  i honestly didnâ€™t care what happened to me, i just wanted to have fun.  these experiences were often accompanied with abusive men, a pair of which lead me to a week long hospital visit in rochester and some permanent damage physical and emotional damage. 
this year i celebrated 2 years completely free of crystal and it is wonderful.  iâ€™ve learned to respect myself and those people who love me.  meth is scary & dangerous & selfish.  it gives you such a false perception of reality for so long that it becomes very hard (and depressing) to live outside that.

i think the worst thing to come out of this is the shame it has made me carry around for the last 2 years.  meth is dirty.  meth is gross.  society make it very clear what they think of people who do meth.  it felt like i was in the closet all over again.  i was so ashamed of myself that i just kept it bottled up and blamed myself over and over.  but blame doesnâ€™t accomplish anything, taking responsibility does.  this year i took responsibility for my past, and i also forgave myself for fucking up. 
i have no regrets, i have learned so much about myself, the world, and this entire experience has brought me closer to discovering my path forward. 
thank you to those of you who have always been there for me, and continue to be.  and to anyone out there whoâ€™s struggling with anything, youâ€™re not alone. -kevin reed

text: 2018 i had to accept what i had been feeling for so long. it was those feelings that didnâ€™t allow me to grow as a person, to be happy, to smile, to let go of the past. depression affected my life in so many ways. it claimed my cousins life, has taken a toll in my dadâ€™s life and my son has been affected by it. i felt depression the most when i had to come to terms with being sexually molested as a child. i never healed. i have accepted certain labels, being a survivor, #metoo, having mental health issues. no iâ€™m not crazy. i have survived a past that could have ended my life.  i am here. although, i tried to be strong for my children i couldnâ€™t be and i wasnâ€™t leading by example. i wanted them to believe in themselves, to be motivated, to have the strength in knowing that we can get past this. i failed to show them self love, acceptance, to believe in themselves. i have struggled with threats, control, and manipulation. to have ended a physically and mentally abusive relationship and to have to admit that my past has affected me to this day.  in the most humble way, i am asking you to share this post. without your help, our struggle will continue. i hope that one day soon iâ€™ll be able to share another post where i can say that we are thriving and no longer just surviving. i have had to see my son be the most affected. i canâ€™t let this continue. somehow we will get past this. thank you for everyone who i have met across this platform. i have read your posts, your words of encouragement. you are truly an inspiration. please keep our family in your prayers. god bless you and your family. please click the link in the bio. ğŸ™ğŸ½

text:
the numeric significance of the calendar year is calculated by adding the digits of said year and reducing it to a single digit.
2+0+1+9= 12. 1+2=3. 
the universal number indicates the collective global vibration for that year, and gives us some insight of the energetic nature of our year to come. 
how you work with that vibration is dependent on you. 
for most, 2018 was a year of challenges and growth. you may have felt lost, confused, but excited. an inner fiery passion made itself known, even if you had no idea where or how to direct that passion. 
the divine feminine began to rise to make way for the union of the healed/balanced feminine and masculine.
the #metoo and #timesup movement were symbolic of the chaotic nature of the numeric "universal 2" year that was 2018. hollywood scandals, corporate greed, environmental distress, political drama..were all begining to be unveiled in their true light.
in 2019 we work with the 3 vibration (one of clarity, light, truth, also the number of ascended masters and the throat chakra) to communicate with our hearts and eachother to bring unity, clarity and a collectively beneficial vision of the future into fruition. 
universal year 3's are exciting ones, as they bring action, creativity, authenticity, compassion and truth to the forefront of our minds. 
if you've been feeling charged but undecided, lost, or confused, 2019 is a pivotal year of finding alignment and following our soul purpose. 
we will no longer be satisfied with living half-heartedly, but rather dive into the depths of our hearts and bring our desires to the forefront. 
universal year 3 is one of joy, communication, change, socializing, and living in pleasure. 
what does this mean for you? whatever you want it to mean. whether you shy away from this newfound energy and choose to live in the confining but familiar old paradigm is up to you. 
for me, i already feel a pull. a need to shed the old conditioning that led me to limit and constrict myself to be versions of myself that suited others. *continued in comments*

text:
scriabin sonata 4 opus. 30, mvt 2 Â· prestissimo
â€”
mitrofan belaiev, outstanding patron of russian composers, scriabinâ€™s publisher since 1894 and his stern, fatherly mentor in worldly matters, had died in december 1903. corresponding to this upheaval in personal life is a transformation in musical language, shown clearly in the sonata no 4, op 30 (1903). for this work scriabin wrote a programme: a poem describing flight to a distant star. it reflects the startling new philosophies he was imbibing:

thinly veiled in transparent cloud
a star shines softly, far and lonely.
how beautiful! the azure secret
of its radiance beckons, lulls me â€¦
vehement desire, sensual, insane, sweet â€¦
now! joyfully i fly upward toward you,
freely i take wing.
mad dance, godlike play â€¦
i draw near in my longing â€¦
drink you in, sea of light, you light of my own self â€¦

these excerpts give a flavour of scriabinâ€™s literary effusion, which hardly does justice to his music. it does, however, contain a number of motifs which recur in his mental world: light, colour, erotic desire, flight, dance, and the equation of the cosmos with the ego. the last-mentioned is close to theÂ tat tvam asiâ€”â€˜that art thouâ€™â€”of sanskrit teaching, the universal oneness of mystic experience in many cultures; with a personality as self-absorbed as scriabin, however, it is possible to feel rather that he believes â€˜all is myself!â€™â€”a rather different proposition.
Â·

text:
mgtow 101: do you know you? 
i see memes circulating like this all over social media, but most people don't really know themselves in relation to the world.

i was having a conversation with a homegirl, and she prompted me to do an experiment. i told her most people just want to he accepted and loved for who they are. part of that requires the spouse to actually know what you bring to the table.

i asked what makes you special?

what makes you standout from all the other women in the world?

she wrote a length 100 word response, and she was all wrong. so i told her from my lenses what separates you from others, and she immediately recognized why her own assessment of herself was wrong and shallow.

she named things that benefit other people and things that men love about her, but didn't name the things that benefits her self or the things that she should love about herself.

if you and your conscious were the only two people on planet what would they say about the other?

i would be willing to bet if i asked majority of men and women they would not know what truly separates them from others. if you don't know shit in this world you need to know yourself.

on the low, this is game for women too. women love to talk about themselves or hear you talk about them. so when you are talking to a woman study her and be able to tell her what makes her special, what separates her from every other person. don't use generic shallow bullshit but traits and skills that she truly possesses that require in depth thinking.

women want to be themselves and be seen for who they are. if they have to wear a mask to be around the guy, that guy won't be respected. they often say i shouldn't have to tell you how i feel, you're the man you supposed to know. the same applies to other areas, they feel they shouldn't need to wear masks you should be able to remove it and know who they are.

most couples are married to masks and the ones that aren't have a much better relationship. to wear a mask is to be enslaved. freedom is being exactly who you are, without having to hide anything especially from your wife or husband. this first requires knowing yourself and being honest about yourself.

text: art + activism = healing. this year, celebrating the 10th anniversary of my first record, disguised as fate, written when i was a traumatized teenage girl, was truly healing and cathartic. organizing on the artivism committee & marching with my girls, women, femmes & queers at the womenâ€™s march 2.0 was empowering and inspiring. remembering jessi zazu through music, organizing arts + activism workshops for youth, a memorial mural & being a part of @jessizazuinc has helped many of us channel grief, passion, and her spirit of creativity & justice. iâ€™ve been introduced to an asian-american community of artists & activists, been featured on some cool podcasts & press, been proud to spread the good work of many organizations through my radio station @wxnafm somatic experiencing has begun to address the trauma in my body, and i am grateful for the #metoo & #timesup movements, making it easier for me to open up and fight against oppression & violence through bystander intervention trainings and grassroots collectives. these are just a few of the things that fueled me as an artist, educator, organizer & activist this year. i hope 2019 finds us continuing to  work for collective healing justice, love & beauty! #topnine2018

text:
"when you wake up in the morning, tell yourself: the people i deal with today will be meddling, ungrateful, arrogant, dishonest, jealous and surly. they are like this because they can't tell good from evil. but i have seen the beauty of good, and the ugliness of evil, and have recognized that the wrongdoer has a nature related to my own - not of the same blood and birth, but the same mind, and possessing a share of the divine. and so none of them can hurt me. no one can implicate me in ugliness. nor can i feel angry at my relative, or hate him. we were born to work together like feet, hands and eyes, like the two rows of teeth, upper and lower. to obstruct each other is unnatural. to feel anger at someone, to turn your back on him: these are unnatural.â€ ~ marcus aurelius
